chunks.html_content:
The early years foundation stage (EYFS) sets standards for the learning, development and care of your child from birth to 5 years old.

All schools and Ofsted-registered early years providers must follow the EYFS, including childminders, preschools, nurseries and school reception classes.
chunks.plain_content:
Early years foundation stage
The early years foundation stage (EYFS) sets standards for the learning, development and care of your child from birth to 5 years old.
All schools and Ofsted-registered early years providers must follow the EYFS, including childminders, preschools, nurseries and school reception classes.

chunks.html_content: The EYFS only applies to schools and early years providers in England. There are different early years standards in Scotland and early years standards in Wales.
chunks.plain_content:
Early years foundation stage
The EYFS only applies to schools and early years providers in England. There are different early years standards in Scotland and early years standards in Wales.

chunks.html_content:
Your child will mostly be taught through games and play.

The areas of learning are:

  • communication and language
  • personal, social and emotional development
  • physical development
  • literacy
  • mathematics
  • understanding the world
  • expressive arts and design
chunks.plain_content:
Early years foundation stage
Areas of learning
Your child will mostly be taught through games and play.
The areas of learning are:

  communication and language
  personal, social and emotional development
  physical development
  literacy
  mathematics
  understanding the world
  expressive arts and design

chunks.html_content:
Your child’s progress will be reviewed when they’re between 2 and 3 by an early years practitioner or health visitor.

Their class teacher will assess them at the end of the school year when they turn 5.

The assessment is based on classroom observation - your child will not be tested. It uses the early learning goals, which can be found in the early years framework.

heading_context: If an area of learning conflicts with your beliefs
chunks.html_content:
Talk to your child’s early years provider if you think one or more areas of the EYFS conflict with your religious or philosophical beliefs. They’ll tell you if you need to ask for an ‘exemption’.

If you get an exemption, your child will not have to take part in a specific area of learning for 12 months.

Write to your early years provider if you decide to ask for an exemption. You must explain how your religious or philosophical beliefs conflict with:

  • an area of learning
  • a learning goal or assessment

Your early years provider will decide if you can get an exemption. If you get one, you’ll need to apply again after 12 months.
